  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT317-kilavi">piriviṭaik kiḻattiyait tōḻi vaṟpuṟuttiyatu. </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">The confidante encouraging HER in the time of
          separation. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT317">
          <l> purimaṭa maraiyāṉ karunarai nallēṟu</l>
          <l> tīmpuḷi nelli mānti yayalatu</l>
          <l> tēmpāy māmalar naṭuṅka veytuyirt</l>
          <l> tōṅkumalaip paiñcuṉai paruku nāṭa</l>
          <l> ṉammaiviṭ ṭamaiyumō maṟṟē kaimmika</l>
          <l> vaṭapula vāṭaik kaḻimaḻai</l>
          <l> teṉpulam paṭarun taṇpaṉi nāḷē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l rend="indent">On a day with cool dew, when the decreasing rain sets out</l>
          <l rend="indent2">for the southern fields before the wind</l>
          <l rend="indent6">from the northern fields, <note place="foot"> Is this the intended statement? Cām. takes both <term xml:lang="ta"> pulam </term> simply as "direction" (but why then not just <term xml:lang="ta"> vaṭa/teṉ</term>?) and does not consider <term xml:lang="ta"> aḻi</term> at all. In any case it seems unavoidable to understand the dative <term xml:lang="ta"> vāṭaikku </term> in the way of an ablative "from – to", because surely nothing can be supposed to set out towards the wind.   </note> overmuch,</l>
          <l>will he really <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> ōmaṟṟē </term> seems to mark a rhetorical question (expecting a negative answer), but what is the exact valence?   </note> let go of us once and for all, <note place="foot"> Here again we see <term xml:lang="ta"> amai-tal </term> as an auxiliary expressing the obtaining of a new, stable state.   </note></l>
          <l>the man from a land, where the black-and-white bull</l>
          <l rend="indent">of the desirous-youthful wild cow is drinking from the fresh pool</l>
          <l rend="indent2">on the high mountain after feeding on sweet-sour Nelli fruit</l>
          <l rend="indent">[and] breathing hot for big blossoms spread with honey</l>
          <l rend="indent9">nearby to tremble? <note place="foot"> T.V.G.'s idea for the rationale of this line is that the flowers on the water would have grown so dense as to form a kind of carpet on the water. By the breath of the thirsty animals the water is rippled so that the plants move apart and allow them to drink. </note> </l>

        </lg>
      </div>
